<subsection xml:id="subsec-construction-of-regular-polygons">
        <title>Construction of regular polygons</title>
        <introduction>
         <p>
            In construction of regular polygons, you shall be using GeoGebra platform with step by step guides for each polygon
        </p>
                
        
        </introduction>
        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Construction-of-a-triangle">
            <title>Construction of a triangle</title>
            <p>
              This activity involves constructing an equilateral triangle, that is, a triangle with sides of equal lengths.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul> 
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>point tool(Window 1),</term> create points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> on the applet.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>segment tool(Window 5),</term> draw a segment by clicking on point <m>A</m> then <m>B.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             Select <term>compass tool(Window 3)</term>. Then click on point <m>A</m> and point <m>B</m> 
                             (It represents how wide the compass is) and again on point <m>A</m> (It represents the sharp end of the compass). 
                             Then click on <m>B</m> and <m>A</m> (It represents the width  opening of the compass) and again on <m>B</m> (It represents the sharp end of the compass).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Select <term>intersect tool(Window 4),</term> and mark a point <m>c</m>,  at the point of intersection of the two circles.  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>segment tool(Window 5),</term> and draw  line segments using points <m>BC</m>and <m>AC.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Hide the two circles by selecting the <term>show/hide object tool(Window 6)</term> and then click on the circles.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Move points <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> and observe what happens to your triangle. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Equilateral triangle</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-equilateral-triangle" platform="geogebra" width="95%" aspect="4:3">
                <slate xml:id="Equilateral-triangle" surface="geogebra" material="qfsbazjq" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>

            <p>
                Share your findings from the activity above with your fellow learneres.
            </p>
        </subsubsection>

        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Square">
            <title>Square</title>
            <p>
                Construct a square in the applet below using the following instructions.
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>point tool(Window 1),</term> create points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> on the applet.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>segment tool(Window 6),</term> draw a segment by clicking on point <m>A</m> then <m>B.</m>                        
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>compass tool(Window 3)</term>. Click on point <m>A</m> and point <m>B</m> 
                             (It represents how wide the compass is) and again on point <m>A.</m> Then click on point 
                             <m>B</m> followed by <m>A</m> and  again on point <m>B.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>intersect tool(Window 5),</term> and  click on the two circles one at a time 
                            to mark points of intersection of the two circles, <m>C</m> and <m>D</m> respectively.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>line tool(Window 4)</term> and click on point 
                            <m>C</m> and then <m>D</m> to construct a line perpendicular to the segment <m>AB.</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                     <li>
                        <p>
                           Select <term>intersect tool(Window 5).</term> Click on segment <m>AB</m> and the perpendicular 
                           line passing trough points <m>C</m>and <m>D</m> to mark a  their point of intersection <m>E.</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>compass tool(Window 3).</term> Click on point <m>E.</m> then <m>B</m>
                            and again on point <m>E</m> to draw a circle with center <m>E</m> and its circumference touching points <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Select <term>intersect tool(Window 5),</term> and mark points <m>F</m> and <m>G</m> respectively,  
                            at the point of intersection of the circle and perpendicular line  passing through points <m>C</m> and <m>D.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select <term>segment tool (Window 6)</term> and draw the line segments <m>AF, FB, BG \text { and } GA</m>
                            to constuct a square.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select the <term>show/hide object tool(Window 8)</term> and hide all objects, leaving only the square. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Select the <term>move tool (Window 7)</term>  Move point <m>A</m> or <m>B.</m> What can you see? Is the quadrilateral a square?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Square</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-square" platform="geogebra" width="95%" aspect="4:3">
                <slate xml:id="square" surface="geogebra" material="m4pccfx9" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>
            <p>
                Discuss your findings with other learners.
            </p>
            
        </subsubsection>

